{{Short description|Sacred mirrors used in Shinto}}
{{Draft topics|east-asia}}
{{AfC topic|soc}}

[[File:高士神社.jpeg|thumb|The [[Gaoshi Shrine]] in Taiwan. The mirror in front of that shrine is a divine mirror.]]
A {{Interlanguage link|Shinto mirror|ja|神鏡}} {{Nihongo|2=神鏡|3=Shinkyou}} is a mirror sacred in [[Shinto]]. Some mirrors are enshrined in the main hall of a shrine as a sacred object of the divine spirit, or are placed in front of the deity in a hall of worship{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}. Mirrors in ancient Japan represented truth because they merely reflected what was shown, and were a source of much mystique and reverence (being uncommon items){{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}. [[Japanese folklore]] is rich in stories of life before mirrors were commonplace.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|last=De_Garis|first=Frederick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hUm0AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA237|title=We Japanese|date=2013-09-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-18367-6|pages=237|language=en}}</ref>

The [[Yata no Kagami]], one of the [[Imperial Regalia of Japan|Three Sacred Treasures]], is also one of the sacred mirrors.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|last=Denney|first=John W.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9ntpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA321|title=Respect and Consideration|date=2011|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-0-9568798-0-6|pages=321, 318-326|language=en}}</ref>

== Significance ==
Spirits are enshrined in Shinto mirrors as [[Shintai]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=日本国語大辞典,デジタル大辞泉,世界大百科事典内言及 |first=精選版 |title=神鏡とは |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%A5%9E%E9%8F%A1-536961 |access-date=2022-05-09 |website=コトバンク |language=ja}}</ref>

<!--As for the significance of the Shinto mirror, it is generally said that it refers to the sun in a mirror. In [[Shintoism]], [[Amaterasu]], the [[Solar deity]], is worshipped and enshrined as the supreme deity. It is said that the mirror symbolizing the sun is used as the [[Shintai]] and enshrined in the shrine{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}.-->In the [[Nihon Shoki]], [[Amaterasu]] tells her grandson, [[Ninigi-no-Mikoto]], "Always worship these mirrors as my soul.

The platform on which this divine mirror is placed is usually in the shape of a cloud, and is called a cloud-shaped platform.<ref>{{Cite book |last=1901-1987 |first=坂本太郎, |url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/123050747 |title=日本書紀 |date=2003.9-2003.11 |publisher=Iwanami shoten |isbn=4-00-007230-7 |oclc=123050747}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=May 2022}}

== History of Shinto mirrors ==
It is said that the origin of the divine mirror dates back to China<ref name=":1" />. In China, more ancient divine mirrors have been unearthed than in Japan, and compared to the oldest mirror in Japan, the "Four Divine Mirrors with a rectangular shape inscribed in the third year of Seiryu," which is dated to 235 A.D., the oldest divine mirror in China is the "Mirror with a leaf vein design," which is an order of magnitude older than Japan, dating from 1600 to 770 B.C.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}} In addition, according to the "[[wajinden]]", [[Himiko]], the queen of the [[Yamatai|Yamatai Kingdom]], sent an envoy to Wei and received a hundred bronze mirrors from Wei, suggesting that Japan's divine mirror culture is a cultural import from China.<ref name=":1" />

The Shinto mirror at Iishi Shrine in Hyogo Prefecture is said to have been introduced by a naturalized celestial spear from [[Silla]]. On the other hand, the Ministry of the Imperial Household issued a notice to official national shrines founded after [[1895]] ([[1895|28th year of Meiji]]) that their sacred objects should be Shinto mirrors.<ref>『神社有職故実』全１２９頁７頁昭和２６年７月１５日神社本庁発行</ref>

== Types of Shinto Mirrors ==

=== Mirror with foliate pattern ===
: This is the oldest divine mirror in the world, dating from 1600 B.C.~770 B.C., and belonging to the [[Shang dynasty]] and [[Zhou dynasty]] of the Chinese dynasty. It is the oldest divine mirror in the world, dating from 1600 B.C.~770 B.C. Even today, only 21 mirrors have been found, and although the bronze mirrors are simple, they show geometric patterns such as leaf vein patterns and parallel lines, which are common in Japanese earthenware. Geometric patterns such as leaf vein patterns and parallel lines, which are common in Japanese earthenware, can be seen.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== Somen mirror ===
: A divine mirror from 770 B.C. to 220 B.C. during the Spring and Autumn Warring States Period. As its name suggests, it is simple and flat in appearance, but its thinness and lightness show the improvement of technology.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== Hanryu Hishimonkyo ===
:: A mirror from 219 BC to 111 BC in the early [[Western Han]] period. Designs of dragons and snakes that wind around the tongue are engraved.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== Mirror of the Four Gods ===
: 1st~2nd century Later Han Dynasty mirror. A square line is carved in the center, and each section is decorated with the designs of four gods: [[Azure Dragon|Blue Dragon]], [[White Tiger (mythology)|White Tiger]], [[Vermilion Bird]], and [[Black Tortoise|Genbu]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== Divine Immortal Image Mirror ===
: A 2nd~3rd century Later Han Chinese divine mirror. The design features carvings of [[Xian (Taoism)|Shen Xian]], [[Old Man of the South Pole|The Old Man of the South Pole]], the Emperor of China, [[King Father of the East|Father of the East]], [[Queen Mother of the West|Mother of the West]], and others.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== The Three-year Inscription of Qinglong's Square and the Four Magic Mirrors ===
This is the oldest mirror in Japan. This mirror is the oldest of its kind in Japan. The year "Seiryu 3" in the inscription of this mirror corresponds to the year 235 AD in the Chinese Wei Dynasty, and in the "Wei Shi Wajin Den", the queen of [[Yamatai|Umataikoku]], [[Himiko]], sent an envoy to [[Cao Wei|Wei]] in the third year of Jingzhuang (239), and returned to Japan in the first year of Shoshi (240). It has been pointed out that this mirror may have been among them.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== Chinese Dragon and Tiger Mirror ===
: Late 3rd-century Han mirror. It is called this because of the dragon and tiger patterns staring at each other in the center.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== Triangular Edge God Beast Mirror ===
This mirror is made of bronze and has a triangular rim.
This type of mirror is made of bronze and has a triangular cross-section with protruding triangles and inscriptions of sacred animals. This type of mirror is found only in Japan, but there are many examples in China and Korea as well.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

It is said to be one of the 100 bronze mirrors given to Himiko by the Wei emperor, but it has not been found in any 3rd century ruins or tombs during the period of the Yamataikoku, but only in the 4th century Kofun period.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}

=== Goryo Shintai ===
In many shrines and palaces, the divine mirror is used as a sacred object. In the Imperial Court, divine mirrors are often referred to as [[Shintai|Goryoyo]]. According to the regulations, "The [[Shinto shrine]]s, [[Emperor of Japan]]s, and [[Tenjin]]s shall have a mirror with a diameter of one shaku, and [[Emperor of Japan]]s shall have a mirror with a diameter of seven shaku. This box is then wrapped in [[Mail]] and placed in a [[Karabitsu]]. It is also possible to wrap the mirror in [[silk]] and place it in the [[Ohiyo]], then in the [[Funashiyo]], and cover it with the [[Goshiki]].<ref>"Shinto Shrine Yushoku Kokusitsu", p. 129, 7, July 1, 1951. Published by the Jinja Main Office on July 1, 1951</ref>

