[[File:高士神社.jpeg|thumb|The [[Gaoshi Shrine]] in Taiwan. The mirror in front of that shrine is a divine mirror.]]
A {{Interlanguage link|Shinto mirror|ja|神鏡}} {{Nihongo|2=神鏡|3=Shinkyou}} is a mirror sacred in [[Shinto]]. Some mirrors are enshrined in the main hall of a shrine as a sacred object of the divine spirit, or are placed in front of the deity in a hall of worship<ref name=":2" />. Mirrors in ancient Japan represented truth because they merely reflected what was shown, and were a source of much mystique and reverence (being uncommon items){{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}. [[Japanese folklore]] is rich in stories of life before mirrors were commonplace.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|last=De_Garis|first=Frederick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hUm0AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA237|title=We Japanese|date=2013-09-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-18367-6|pages=237|language=en}}</ref>

The [[Yata no Kagami]], one of the [[Imperial Regalia of Japan|Three Sacred Treasures]], is also one of the sacred mirrors.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|last=Denney|first=John W.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9ntpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA321|title=Respect and Consideration|date=2011|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-0-9568798-0-6|pages=321, 318-326|language=en}}</ref>

== Significance ==
Spirits are enshrined in divine mirrors as [[Shintai]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=日本国語大辞典,デジタル大辞泉,世界大百科事典内言及 |first=精選版 |title=神鏡とは |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%A5%9E%E9%8F%A1-536961 |access-date=2022-05-09 |website=コトバンク |language=ja}}</ref>

<!--As for the significance of the Shinto mirror, it is generally said that it refers to the sun in a mirror. In [[Shintoism]], [[Amaterasu]], the [[Solar deity]], is worshipped and enshrined as the supreme deity. It is said that the mirror symbolizing the sun is used as the [[Shintai]] and enshrined in the shrine{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}}.-->In the [[Nihon Shoki]], [[Amaterasu]] tells her grandson, [[Ninigi-no-Mikoto]], "Always worship these mirrors as my soul. The platform on which this divine mirror is placed is usually in the shape of a cloud, and is called a cloud-shaped platform".<ref>{{Cite book |last=1901-1987 |first=坂本太郎, |url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/123050747 |title=日本書紀 |date=2003.9-2003.11 |publisher=Iwanami shoten |isbn=4-00-007230-7 |oclc=123050747}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=May 2022}}

== History of divine mirrors ==
It is said that the origin of the divine mirror dates back to China<ref name=":1" />. In China, more ancient divine mirrors have been unearthed than in Japan, and compared to the oldest mirror in Japan, the "Four divine mirrors with a rectangular shape inscribed in the third year of Seiryu," which is dated to 235 A.D., the oldest divine mirror in China is the "{{Nihongo|Leaf Vein Mirror|葉脈文鏡|Yōmyaku bun kagami}}," which is an order of magnitude older than Japan, dating from 1600 to 770 B.C.{{Citation needed|date=March 2022}} In addition, according to the "[[wajinden]]", [[Himiko]], the queen of the [[Yamatai|Yamatai Kingdom]], sent an envoy to Wei and received a hundred bronze mirrors from Wei, suggesting that Japan's divine mirror culture is a cultural import from China.<ref name=":1" />

The divine mirror at Iishi Shrine in Hyogo Prefecture is said to have been introduced by a naturalized celestial spear from [[Silla]]. On the other hand, the Ministry of the Imperial Household issued a notice to official national shrines founded after [[1895]] ([[1895|28th year of Meiji]]) that their sacred objects should be divine mirrors.<ref>『神社有職故実』全１２９頁７頁昭和２６年７月１５日神社本庁発行</ref>

