[[File:高士神社.jpeg|thumb|The [[Gaoshi Shrine]] in Taiwan. The mirror in front of that shrine is a divine mirror.]] A {{Interlanguage link|Shinto mirror|ja|神鏡}} {{Nihongo|2=神鏡|3=Shinkyou}} is a mirror sacred in [[Shinto]]. Some mirrors are enshrined in the main hall of a shrine as a sacred object of the divine spirit, or are placed in front of the deity in a hall of worship<ref name=":2" />. Mirrors in ancient Japan represented truth because they merely reflected what was shown, and were a source of much mystique and reverence <ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-01-06 |title=Yata No Kagami - The Sacred Mirror of Japan {{!}} Suki Desu |url=https://skdesu.com/en/yata-no-kagami-the-sacred-mirror-of-japan/ |access-date=2022-05-09 |language=en-US}}</ref>. [[Japanese folklore]] is rich in stories of life before mirrors were commonplace.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|last=De_Garis|first=Frederick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hUm0AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA237|title=We Japanese|date=2013-09-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-18367-6|pages=237|language=en}}</ref>
The [[Yata no Kagami]], one of the [[Imperial Regalia of Japan|Three Sacred Treasures]], is also one of the sacred mirrors.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|last=Denney|first=John W.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9ntpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA321|title=Respect and Consideration|date=2011|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-0-9568798-0-6|pages=321, 318-326|language=en}}</ref>
